g eget at enim. Nulla sed fermentum elit. Nunc id magna purus.<br><\\/p>\",\"87\":[\"35\",\"132\"]}}','2015-05-07 02:36:49','2015-05-07 02:36:49','9cb0d4a0-411a-4b75-9d0d-51001b0c5ac5'),(360,88,19,281,'en_us',8,'','{\"typeId\":\"23\",\"authorId\":null,\"title\":\"About The Gathering Place\",\"slug\":\"aboutus\",\"postDate\":1425505690,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"205\":\"<p>When you walk through the doors of The Gathering Place you will see art throughout our space. Art that has been donated to us by individuals and families. You will also see art created by our participants in our art therapy programs. Art is an opportunity to explore the feelings that come with a cancer journey and express them using the creativity that is within each of us.<\\/p>\",\"207\":\"<p>The Gathering Place East was opened in Beachwood in January 2000 to meet the needs of individuals and families touched by cancer. The facility in Beachwood includes Norma\'s Garden, a beautiful, healing space that includes paths for walking and spaces to sit and meditate. In 2011, The Richman Family Wellness Center was opened to address the side effects from cancer treatment like fatigue and to help build strength and stamina. The Gathering Place East is located at 23300 Commerce Park. The Gathering Place Richman Family Wellness Center is located at 23295 Commerce Park. Regardless of which facility you go to access the programs and services offered by The Gathering Place you will find a caring and supportive staff and the same types of programs to help you and your family cope with a cancer diagnosis.<span><\\/span> <\\/p>\",\"135\":\"<p>In 1998, Eileen Saffran told the community a story. This story was about a space where people on a cancer journey could seek support. A space where people felt safe, connected with others, and found peace during a time of chaos. A space where the entire family was supported, the services were free, and the largest barrier to entry was admitting you needed help. The story resonated with people in the community and as it unfolded, more people listened.<\\/p><p>A grass roots effort began in a small conference room and ended in an auditorium. Listening turned into action. Those who heard the story became donors, volunteers, staff members and ambassadors. The story came to life and The Gathering Place was created.<\\/p><p>The Gathering Place opened its doors in Beachwood in 2000. In 2008 a location was opened in Westlake and in 2011 The Gathering Place Richman Family Wellness Center opened in Beachwood to provide exercise programs for individuals in treatment and those that had completed treatment. Since opening its doors 15 years ago, The Gathering Place has served over 35,000 individuals who have made more than 271,000 visits.<br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p>\",\"203\":\"The mission of The Gathering Place is to support, educate and empower individuals and families touched by cancer through programs and services provided free of charge.\",\"204\":\"<p>The programs at The Gathering Place heal the body, the mind and the spirit.  We recognize that everyone has different needs while on the cancer journey and we provide programs and services to meet people where they are on the journey. Whether you are the person with cancer or their loved one, cancer impacts how you see the world. Our job at The Gathering Place is to help you see things differently; to help you see life moving forward, during and after cancer. Seeing things differently could mean accepting a diagnosis, finding forgiveness, or releasing anger. <\\/p><p>People often describe feeling a sense of peace when they walk through our doors. This comes from being a part of a community. This comes from feeling safe and connected.   This comes from knowing you are not alone on your journey.<\\/p>\",\"206\":\"<ul><li>Short term one-to-one counseling and support groups help participants find ways to cope with the emotional impact of a cancer diagnosis<\\/li><li>There are weekly groups for those diagnosed with cancer and one for \\r\\nfamily and friends, as well as monthly or quarterly drop-in groups for specific cancers \\r\\nsuch as breast, prostate, blood cancers and oral, head and neck cancers.<\\/li><li>Two education centers that include lending libraries with over 2,500 books, cds and dvds provide information and opportunities to learn more about coping and provide practical information<\\/li><li> The medical librarian will help you research any questions you may have on cancer and its treatment, whether you are newly diagnosed, a long-term survivor or a family member seeking information<\\/li><li>Lectures and workshops by local experts offer the latest information on cancer treatments and complementary medicine<\\/li><li>Reiki, massage and reflexology can help reduce stress and manage pain<\\/li><li>Gentle movement classes such as tai chi, yoga and qigong help to rebuild strength and balance and reduce stress<\\/li><li>Exercise classes led by certified fitness trainers help to address the physical side effects of cancer treatment and help to build strength and increase stamina<\\/li><li>One-to-one consultations with a licensed dietitian as well as hands-on cooking classes help to enhance or create a more healthy life style<\\/li><li>Comprehensive individual and group programs that meet the needs of children and teens coping with an adult family members cancer <\\/li><li>Art and music programs help individuals tap into their creativity to explore and express the emotions that come up during the cancer journey<\\/li><li>Regina Brett Wig Salons provide a free wig to women with cancer-related hair loss<\\/li><\\/ul>\",\"176\":[\"116\"],\"87\":[\"35\",\"113\"],\"167\":{\"185\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":\"\",\"siteImageCaption\":\"Football Cat\",\"imageSite\":[\"119\"]}},\"186\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":[\"134\"],\"siteImageCaption\":\"Lighthouse\",\"imageSite\":[\"120\"]}},\"187\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":[\"109\"],\"siteImageCaption\":\"Janis\",\"imageSite\":[\"119\"]}},\"188\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":\"\",\"siteImageCaption\":\"Walrus\",\"imageSite\":[\"120\"]}}},\"208\":\"<p>The Gathering Place West is located in Westlake and opened in October of 2008. This facility provides those living west of the Cuyahoga an opportunity to utilize our programs and services a little closer to home. The Gathering Place is located at 800 Sharon Drive.  Regardless of which facility  you go to access the programs and services offered by The Gathering Place you will find a caring and supportive staff and the same types of programs to help you and your family cope with a cancer diagnosis.<\\/p>\"}}','2015-05-26 13:23:27','2015-05-26 13:23:27','b317a3ce-ec06-43d6-b4cd-1fa7829ca462'),(361,88,19,281,'en_us',9,'','{\"typeId\":\"23\",\"authorId\":null,\"title\":\"About The Gathering Place\",\"slug\":\"aboutus\",\"postDate\":1425505690,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"205\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tWhen you walk through the doors of The Gathering Place you will see art throughout our space. Art that has been donated to us by individuals and families. You will also see art created by our participants in our art therapy programs. Art is an opportunity to explore the feelings that come with a cancer journey and express them using the creativity that is within each of us.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"207\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tThe Gathering Place East was opened in Beachwood in January 2000 to meet the needs of individuals and families touched by cancer. The facility in Beachwood includes Norma\'s Garden, a beautiful, healing space that includes paths for walking and spaces to sit and meditate. In 2011, The Richman Family Wellness Center was opened to address the side effects from cancer treatment like fatigue and to help build strength and stamina. The Gathering Place East is located at 23300 Commerce Park. The Gathering Place Richman Family Wellness Center is located at 23295 Commerce Park. Regardless of which facility you go to access the programs and services offered by The Gathering Place you will find a caring and supportive staff and the same types of programs to help you and your family cope with a cancer diagnosis.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"135\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tIn 1998, Eileen Saffran told the community a story. This story was about a space where people on a cancer journey could seek support. A space where people felt safe, connected with others, and found peace during a time of chaos. A space where the entire family was supported, the services were free, and the largest barrier to entry was admitting you needed help. The story resonated with people in the community and as it unfolded, more people listened.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tA grass roots effort began in a small conference room and ended in an auditorium. Listening turned into action. Those who heard the story became donors, volunteers, staff members and ambassadors. The story came to life and The Gathering Place was created.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tThe Gathering Place opened its doors in Beachwood in 2000. In 2008 a location was opened in Westlake and in 2011 The Gathering Place Richman Family Wellness Center opened in Beachwood to provide exercise programs for individuals in treatment and those that had completed treatment. Since opening its doors 15 years ago, The Gathering Place has served over 35,000 individuals who have made more than 271,000 visits.\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"203\":\"The mission of The Gathering Place is to support, educate and empower individuals and families touched by cancer through programs and services provided free of charge.\",\"204\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tThe programs at The Gathering Place heal the body, the mind and the spirit.  We recognize that everyone has different needs while on the cancer journey and we provide programs and services to meet people where they are on the journey. Whether you are the person with cancer or their loved one, cancer impacts how you see the world. Our job at The Gathering Place is to help you see things differently; to help you see life moving forward, during and after cancer. Seeing things differently could mean accepting a diagnosis, finding forgiveness, or releasing anger.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tPeople often describe feeling a sense of peace when they walk through our doors. This comes from being a part of a community. This comes from feeling safe and connected.   This comes from knowing you are not alone on your journey.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"206\":\"<ul>\\r\\n\\t<li>Short term one-to-one counseling and support groups help participants find ways to cope with the emotional impact of a cancer diagnosis<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>There are weekly groups for those diagnosed with cancer and one for \\r\\nfamily and friends, as well as monthly or quarterly drop-in groups for specific cancers \\r\\nsuch as breast, prostate, blood cancers and oral, head and neck cancers.\\r\\n\\t<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Two education centers that include lending libraries with over 2,500 books, cds and dvds provide information and opportunities to learn more about coping and provide practical information<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li> The medical librarian will help you research any questions you may have on cancer and its treatment, whether you are newly diagnosed, a long-term survivor or a family member seeking information<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Lectures and workshops by local experts offer the latest information on cancer treatments and complementary medicine<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Reiki, massage and reflexology can help reduce stress and manage pain<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Gentle movement classes such as tai chi, yoga and qigong help to rebuild strength and balance and reduce stress<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Exercise classes led by certified fitness trainers help to address the physical side effects of cancer treatment and help to build strength and increase stamina<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>One-to-one consultations with a licensed dietitian as well as hands-on cooking classes help to enhance or create a more healthy life style<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Comprehensive individual and group programs that meet the needs of children and teens coping with an adult family members cancer <\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Art and music programs help individuals tap into their creativity to explore and express the emotions that come up during the cancer journey<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Regina Brett Wig Salons provide a free wig to women with cancer-related hair loss<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\",\"176\":[\"116\"],\"87\":[\"35\",\"113\"],\"167\":{\"185\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":\"\",\"siteImageCaption\":\"Football Cat\",\"imageSite\":[\"119\"]}},\"186\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":[\"134\"],\"siteImageCaption\":\"Lighthouse\",\"imageSite\":[\"120\"]}},\"187\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":[\"109\"],\"siteImageCaption\":\"Janis\",\"imageSite\":[\"119\"]}},\"188\":{\"type\":\"siteImage\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"siteImageFile\":\"\",\"siteImageCaption\":\"Walrus\",\"imageSite\":[\"120\"]}}},\"208\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tThe Gathering Place West is located in Westlake and opened in October of 2008. This facility provides those living west of the Cuyahoga an opportunity to utilize our programs and services a little closer to home. The Gathering Place is located at 800 Sharon Drive.  Regardless of which facility  you go to access the programs and services offered by The Gathering Place you will find a caring and supportive staff and the same types of programs to help you and your family cope with a cancer diagnosis.\\r\\n<\\/p>\"}}','2015-05-26 13:54:17','2015-05-26 13:54:17','c9b513d6-07a8-499b-a7cb-aa003128628b'),(362,285,4,281,'en_us',1,'','{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"281\",\"title\":\"Creating Art to Make A Difference\",\"slug\":\"creating-art-to-make-a-difference\",\"postDate\":1432598400,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"174\":[\"118\"],\"177\":\"\",\"175\":\"\",\"176\":\"\",\"144\":\"\",\"87\":\"\",\"67\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"storyInfoBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"storyHeaderImage\":[\"282\"],\"storySubtitle\":\"\",\"storyText\":\"<p>For the last 10 years Kathy Johnson has held a fund-raiser at her shop Hudson Fine Art &amp; Framing through the month of October called \\\"In The Pink\\\". She invites local artists as well as participants from The Gathering Place and her staff to decorate and donate a small canvas. Her talented posse uses every conceivable medium to create a fantastical array of styles and images. Whether it is oil paint, watercolor, acrylic, collage, fiber or photography, the square canvasses run the gamut of realistic to abstract, whimsical to words.The seasoned professionals and enthusiastic contingent from The Gathering Place whip up amazing and imaginative creations. <\\/p><p>Kathy says that with each subsequent year, the number of canvases submitted exceeds her expectations, so that the hardest thing for her is hanging them in straight rows for display! Each October, there is an evening reception at the beginning of the month, with wine poured by her husband\\/sommelier and delicious snacks. Party-goers that night get the first glimpse of the 50 to 75 works that they can bid on, but the display stays up for the entire month for everyone to get a chance to vote for their favorite. Conducted in the manner of a \'Chinese Auction\', anyone can buy raffle tickets and specify which piece they hope to win, depending on what strikes their fancy. <\\/p><p>In 2014, there was a tie for the \\\"People\'s Choice \\\" award, with half of the votes going to five year old Robert McIsacc who painted a pastoral scene of a barn. While it may have been his loving family and friends who stuffed the ballot box, his winning was especially touching because he lost his mother to cancer soon after the show opened. Hudson is a small town where you never know whose life you will touch; Kathy\'s husband had coached Robert\'s sisters in softball. Kathy knows that pain of loss. Her friend Joy Wilson and five other friends all had breast cancer before they were 40. She wanted to find a way to give back and help others, and she is glad to have made The Gathering Place connection. Her event raises over $1,000 each year to support the free programs and services provided at The Gathering Place. <\\/p>\",\"additionalImages\":[\"283\",\"284\"]}}},\"279\":\"\"}}','2015-05-26 14:37:34','2015-05-26 14:37:34','7f11a0a9-9f7e-4a75-b2a8-60e1ba72ad7d'),(363,285,4,281,'en_us',2,'','{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"281\",\"title\":\"Creating Art to Make A Difference\",\"slug\":\"creating-art-to-make-a-difference\",\"postDate\":1432598400,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"174\":[\"118\"],\"177\":\"\",\"175\":\"\",\"176\":\"\",\"144\":\"\",\"87\":\"\",\"67\":{\"286\":{\"type\":\"storyInfoBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"storyHeaderImage\":[\"242\"],\"storySubtitle\":\"\",\"storyText\":\"<p>For the last 10 years Kathy Johnson has held a fund-raiser at her shop Hudson Fine Art &amp; Framing through the month of October called \\\"In The Pink\\\". She invites local artists as well as participants from The Gathering Place and her staff to decorate and donate a small canvas. Her talented posse uses every conceivable medium to create a fantastical array of styles and images. Whether it is oil paint, watercolor, acrylic, collage, fiber or photography, the square canvasses run the gamut of realistic to abstract, whimsical to words.The seasoned professionals and enthusiastic contingent from The Gathering Place whip up amazing and imaginative creations. <\\/p><p>Kathy says that with each subsequent year, the number of canvases submitted exceeds her expectations, so that the hardest thing for her is hanging them in straight rows for display! Each October, there is an evening reception at the beginning of the month, with wine poured by her husband\\/sommelier and delicious snacks. Party-goers that night get the first glimpse of the 50 to 75 works that they can bid on, but the display stays up for the entire month for everyone to get a chance to vote for their favorite. Conducted in the manner of a \'Chinese Auction\', anyone can buy raffle tickets and specify which piece they hope to win, depending on what strikes their fancy. <\\/p><p>In 2014, there was a tie for the \\\"People\'s Choice \\\" award, with half of the votes going to five year old Robert McIsacc who painted a pastoral scene of a barn. While it may have been his loving family and friends who stuffed the ballot box, his winning was especially touching because he lost his mother to cancer soon after the show opened. Hudson is a small town where you never know whose life you will touch; Kathy\'s husband had coached Robert\'s sisters in softball. Kathy knows that pain of loss. Her friend Joy Wilson and five other friends all had breast cancer before they were 40. She wanted to find a way to give back and help others, and she is glad to have made The Gathering Place connection. Her event raises over $1,000 each year to support the free programs and services provided at The Gathering Place. <\\/p>\",\"additionalImages\":[\"283\",\"284\"]}}},\"279\":\"\"}}','2015-05-26 14:39:06','2015-05-26 14:39:06','ffd56f9b-e33b-4a3c-ae5f-31ee0f77dee4'),(364,116,7,281,'en_us',8,'','{\"typeId\":\"8\",\"authorId\":\"4\",\"title\":\"Art & Music\",\"slug\":\"art-music\",\"postDate\":1432665900,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"174\":[\"82\",\"83\"],\"184\":[\"287\"],\"177\":\"\",\"135\":\"<p>Art and music classes provide an opportunity to tap into one\'s creativity and explore and express the emotions that come up while on the cancer journey. The programs are for those currently dealing with cancer in their 